<section id="security-intro">
<title>Introduction</title>

<para>
The two areas of concern related to the security of Inca are the
collection and storage of data. 
</para>

<para>
In regard to security of data collection, the following types of attacks 
should be prevented:
</para>

<itemizedList>
  <listItem>
		<para>
		A malicious reporter executes on a resource and either attempts to
    compromise the resource or report false data.
    </para>
  </listItem>
  <listItem>
    <para>
		An attacker gains control over a reporter manager or a reporter agent and
		attempts to load the system by running reporters at a very high
    frequency.
    </para>
  </listItem>
  <listItem>
		<para>
		An attacker attempts to impersonate a reporter manager and send false data
    about one or more resources to the depot.
    </para>
  </listItem>
</itemizedList>

<para>
In regard to security of data storage, the following types of attacks 
should be prevented:
</para>

<itemizedList>
  <listItem>
    <para>
		An attacker attempts to change or delete data on the depot (e.g., by
    breaking into the database).
    </para>
  </listItem>
  <listItem>
    <para>
    An attacker attempts to impersonate a depot with their own depot.
    </para>
  </listItem>
</itemizedList>

<para>
Second, reporters need access to a valid set of credentials in order 
to test Grid functionality.  Inca should facilitate the propagation of
credentials to resources so that an Inca administrator does not have to log
into every machine in order to maintain an up-to-date set of credentials.
</para>

</section>
